This paper is likely to belong to the Speech and Dialogue (cs.SD) sub-category as it proposes a method for Text-to-Speech synthesis. Additionally, it uses a sequence-to-sequence based system, which is commonly used in speech and dialogue research. 

It could also belong to the Computation and Language (cs.CL) sub-category as it deals with natural language processing and generation. 

The paper also uses Variational AutoEncoders (VAEs) and Householder Flows, which are techniques commonly used in machine learning and deep learning research. Therefore, it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and/or the Signal and Image Processing (cs.SI) sub-categories. 

Finally, the paper proposes a method for improving the perceived emotional intensity of synthesized speech, which could make it relevant to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
